The wind North and went around with the sun arrived in Rockland at 10 A.M. hauled in to Clarkes wharf in the evening.
The wind Southerly and rainy in the morning cleared of in the forenoon with the wind N.W. and commensed dischar finished at 5.PM
The wind Southerly took in 50 bags of meal for Mrs. Hammond started for home at 2 oclock P.M. out all night calm
Calm in the morning was between Bakers Island and duck Islands at sunrise The wind breezed up to the southard and foggy went  through the Western way
notes: assumed N for Southward in am

journal_entry: The wind NE in the morning went around to the Southard got home at noon and landed freight recd letter from Benj. Kittridge G. L. Hodgkins
The wind Southerly work in the shop in forenoon on wheel barrow landed freight in after noon
The wind Southerly and foggy started to go to Bar Harbor moderate ate and went back finished wheel barrow
location: Winter Harbor, Bar Habor, Winter Harbor

journal_entry: The wind Northerly and rainy took scow of Iron Bound and went to Stave Island
location: Winter Harbor, Iron Bound, Stave Island

journal_entry: The wind N.W. in forenoon and hauled around to the S.W. in afternoon went ot Bar Harbor in the Amulet and from store to jordans River
location: Winter Harbor, Bar Harbor, Jordan River

journal_entry: The wind Southerly went to Ellsworth by land got deed made out by Arno Wiswell.  came back to go Jordans River took of one load of wood in scow
The wind N.W. got of two scow loads of wood
The wind South West got of two loads of wood in scow
The wind S.S.E. rainy in afternoon took of two loads of wood
The wind N.W. got of apart of a load of wood took pilot Daniel Foster and came out the river got to Cranberry Isles.
The wind N.W. blowed very heavy fot under way and went to N.E. Harbor took tea with Kate Smallidge
The wind South Easterly got underway at N.E. Harbor at Sunrise and Anchored in Rockland at 9 P.M.
The wind S.E. rainy hauled into Birds wharf Commenced discharging at noon
The wind Easterly and rainy in forenoon in the afternoon Northerly and clear commences onloading again one oclock finished at 3 hauled to Spears wharf after meal for Benj. Kittridge
The wind Easterly and clear took in, 500 bush meal for Benj. Kittridge got to Fox Island at sunset
The wind Southerly started from Fox Island in the morning and got to Bar Harbor at 4 oclock P.M and land 440 bushels meals
The wind Southerly and foggy got underway and came home. recd letter from Henry Geyer
The wind southerly and clear
The wind S.W. blowed heavy and thick of fog filed saws and Jobbing around home
The wind Northerly wrote letter Henry Geyer and Hannah Goodwin
The wind South West left home for Jordans river arrived at sunset landed 60 bushels meal for Benj. Kittridge
The wind Northerly hauled on landing to load
The wind N.E. overcast got hold full of wood
The wind Easterly commenced putting on deck load hauled of in the river at night
The wind South Easterly smart breeze with rain in afternoon
calm and hot all day took one scow load of in the forenoon and another in the night and finished loading
The wind N.E. rainy thick no chance to get out of the river
The wind N.N.E. clear blowing very heavy came out of the River and got to S.W. Harbor
The wind N.E. blowing very heavy and clear got underway at noon arrived at Rockland at 6 P.M. hauled into the wharf in the night
The wind N.N.E. commenced discharching in the afternoon
The wind very moderate to the Eastward finished onloading in the forenoon at 10 oclock
The wind Easterly and very moderate until 2.PM When the wind came South West. and we started for home arrived at Deer Isle at sunset
The wind N.W. got under way and went to Bass Harbor until the wind moderated arrived at home at dark recd letter from Thomas Bunker and Nathan Goodwin
location: Deer Isle, Bass Harbor, Winter Harbor

journal_entry: The wind Southerly to rough to go loading
The wind N.W. went to Bar Harbor to see Mr. Kittridge about the signal
location: Winter Harbor, Bar Harbor, Winter Harbor

journal_entry: The wind South west went on Iron Bound to load nearly filled the hold in afternoon then went into Stave Island Harbor
location: Winter Harbor, Iron Bound, Stave Island

journal_entry: The wind N.N.W. blowed heavy could not go to loading
The wind very moderate in forenoon fresh breeze in afternoon could not go to loading and walked home. Recd letter from Benj. Kittridge
notes: changed Kittredge to Kittridge, Georgia Foss baby died AM. was crossed out

journal_entry: The wind southerly Georgia Foss baby died AM.
The wind South very fresh breeze and rough could not load wrote letter to Post master West Tremont S. D. Parsons Bangor
The wind South East blowed very heavy and rained all day work in shop
The wind Southerly and moderate gathered beets and carrots
Calm and foggy went gunning and got 5 coots back home at noon. Recd letters from Benj. Kittridge and A. N. Willey gathered garden.
Calm in forenoon southerly in afternoon went to Iron Bound and got 3 cords and came home in vessel
location: Winter Harbor, Iron Bound, Winter Harbor

journal_entry: The wind N.N.W. could not load recd letter from Perley and Russell wrote letters to Chas Eaton Greens Landing and Benj. Kittridge
Calm all day T. H. Smallidge and wife dined with me
The wind SSE. rainy and blow wrote letters to A.N. Willey and. Geo. N. Loomis hung grindstone
The wind very moderate to the southward and rough worked on A. G. Brooks foremast
The wind S.W. blowed very heavy and rough
The wind N.W. blowed heavy in the forenoon and N.E and S.E, in the afternoon went to Iron Bound to finish loading got of 1 1/2 scowloads in the evening and went into Stave Island Harbor at 11 P.M.
location: Winter Harbor, Iron Bound, Stave Island

journal_entry: The wind Easterly and rainy got under way from Stave Island and came home
The wind West blowed heavy caulked the scow. went to Lodge of Good Templars and installed officers had a supper
local_place: Home, Lodge of Good Templars, Home

journal_entry: The wind W.S.W. took dinner with Capt Thomas Smallidge
The wind W.est worked one half day on school house bell acknowledged deed for Mrs Warren Young.
The wind N.N.W. in morning got under way and started for Iron Bound to finish loading took the wind W. by S. and went into Stave Island harbor
location: Winter Harbor, Iron Bound, Stave Island

journal_entry: The wind N.N.W. heavy breeze got under way and went home gave up finish loading
The wind Westerly getting ready to go to Rockland filled water repaired boat etc.
The wind Easterly in morning and very moderate got under way and went out for Rockland in the afternoon the wind out to the south East got N.E. Harbor at 7 P.M.
The wind N.E.by.E. got to Deer Isle at 4
The wind N.W.by W. got to Deer Island at 4.P.M.
The wind N.N.W. got to Rockland at 1.P.M. hauled into Mr Birds wharf
The wind NW. got onloaded wrote to my wife
The wind East blowed heavy could not get out of the dock until flood tide in afternoon then went Gilky's Harbor with the wind South bound for Bangor
The wind North West got underway at 9 and anchored above winter Port at 6
The wind N.N.W. lay at anchor all day could not get up river
The wind N.W.est towed to Bangor arrived at 8 A.M. took up with laths shingles and posts for Boston. took on board 75000 laths
The wind Easterly and snowed took dinner on board the A. G. Brooks. wrote letter to Mrs F. R. Bunker and Benj. Kittridge
notes: changed Kittredge to Kittridge, changed & to and

journal_entry: The wind very moderate Northerly. finished loading
The wind Easterly and rainy Towed down to Bucks Ledge apart of the tow went ashore stove the boat lost figure head cut water etc. sailed down to Bucksport
The wind Westerly layed into Bucksport for temporary repairs write letters home and Galen Smith
The wind Northerly fixed up in the forenoon ready to sail. recd of  $5.00 on note got underway at noon arrived at Gilkie's Harbor at sunset
The wind North West in forenoon S.W. afternoon got underway in morning arrived at Tennants Harbor at dark
The wind from N.to.N.W. came out of Tennants Harbor at daylight arrived at Portland at midnight.
The wind Easterly and moderate. layed to an anchor in Portland wrote letters home to Benj. Kittridge Mrs. L. Hammond and C. Stevens
notes: changes & to and, changed Kittredge to Kittridge

journal_entry: The wind N.N.E. thick snow all day layed in Portland
notes: wrote letter H Ro was crossed

journal_entry: The wind very moderate from N.W. to S.W. layed in Portland wrote letter to H. Ross of Bangor. sent papers home by mail. Ellsworth American and New Sensation
The wind N.W. very heavy breeze came out Portland at sunrise anchored in Portsmouth at dark
The wind N.N.E. thick of snow sent home a postal card
The wind N.W. heavy winds got underway in Portsmouth in morning arrived at Gloucester at 4 P.M.
The wind N.W got under way in Gloucester at 3. A.M. arrived in Boston roads at noon and at City at night
The N.W.est. winds hauled through the bridges to Boston and Albany Rail Road wharf
The wind N.N.W. commenced discharging in evening. wrote letter to my wife and recd one from her also from B. Kittridge and Mrs. L. Hammond
The wind very moderate E.N.E. snowed all day finished discharging in evening hauled down through the bridges recd letter from my wife
Calm all day warm and foggy hauled into commercial wharf
The wind about S.S.W. blowed very heavy hauled to T. wharf wrote letter home
The wind North West took in some freight
The wind N.N.W. took in some freight for Bar Harbor. and got ready to sail for home
The wind North a scant wind to go home. layed at the wharf
The wind North West in the morning got underway for home got down to Long Island Boston Harbor and took the wind to the Eastward very moderate and went back to Boston flats
location: Albany Railroad Wharf, Long Island, Boston Harbor, Boston Flats

journal_entry: The wind S.W.byW. rainy a little in the forenoon got underway in forenoon and got to Portsmouth at 6 P.M.
The wind N.N.West blew very heavy layed at anchor at Portsmouth
The wind from West to West South West got underway in Portsmouth in morning anchored in Portland at 2 PM. wrote letter home snowed in afternoon
Clam all day and rainy layed in Portland
The wind N.East and snowed blew fresh
The wind North West got underway in portland at 8 oclock fine breeze got in Tennants Harbor at 6. oclock P.M.
The wind N.N.W.to.N.N.E got underway in Tennants Harbor at day light anchored in Deer Isles at noon waited for the wind to moderate and got underway at 2 oclock and got to Bass Harbor at dark
location: Tenants Harbor, Deer Isle, Bass Harbor

journal_entry: The wind West S.West got underway at day light and got home at one oclock and set up with Stillman Smallidge all night recd letters from Thomas Bunker Hale and Emery Continal life Ins Co.
letter_from: Thomas Bunker, Hale and Emery Continal Life Ins Co

journal_entry: The wind Southerly Stillman Smallidge died at 6:45 A.M. help dress him etc.
The wind very moderate and warm Southerly went to the lower Harbor to see Daniel Southard
local_place: Home, Lower Harbor, Daniel Southard's, Home

journal_entry: The wind North Easterly and warm went to Prospect Harbor to see Frank Summer. Stillman Smallidge duneral preached by Mr. Bither staid with Capt Smallidge
The wind N.East snowed cleared snow of deck staid at Capt Smallidge
The wind Northerly staid at Capt Smallidge's
The wind Westerly took freight out the Amulet and put it on board A. G. Brooks to go to Bar Harbor stoped at Capt Smallidge
location: Prospect Harbor, Bar Harbor, Winter Harbor

journal_entry: The wind Easterly in morning very cold went to Bar Harbor in A. G. Brooks to land Benj. Kittridge freight
location: Winter Harbor, Bar Harbor, Winter Harbor

journal_entry: The wind North Easterly very moderate hauled the Amulet in the wharf and took out load for myself and J. F. Kingsley. Married Joseph Bickford and Miss Annier Springer recd therefor $2.00
The wind North West commenced to burn coal took dunnage out of vessel
The wind N.E.ast hauled a load of wood
The wind North East wrote letter to Ellsworth American. turned Indian clubs for Mr Howard Tacher went to Lodge of Good Templars. snowed in evening
The wind North East snowed in forenoon and North West in afternoon
The wind West Wrote letters to D. T. Tyler and Thomas Bunker
The wind North west made Organ Stool for Montgammery Hammond
The wind very moderate to the Southward hauled the Amulet up for winter
